r-law decay $\\bar{(m_L^{surf})^k}\n\\propto L^{- x_S}$ with $x_S=\\omega_c (1+a)$ independently of the order $k$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Nov 2011 09:38:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 9 Dec 2011 08:41:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-01-18"}
{"id":"1111.3469","submitter":"Serge Bouc","authors":"Serge Bouc (LAMFA)","title":"The Roquette category of finite p-groups","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.CT math.RT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let p be a prime number. This paper introduces the Roquette category R_p of\nfinite p-groups, which is an additive tensor category containing all finite\np-groups among its objects. In R_p, every finite p-group P admits a canonical\ndirect summand, called the edge of P. Moreover P splits uniquely as a direct\nsum of edges of Roquette p-groups, and the tensor structure of R_p can be\ndescribed in terms of such edges. The main motivation for considering this\ncategory is that the additive functors from R_p to abelian groups are exactly\nthe rational p-biset functors. This yields in particular very efficient ways of\ncomputing such functors on arbitrary p-groups : this applies to the\nrepresentation functors R_K, where K is any field of characteristic 0, but also\nto the functor of units of Burnside rings, or to the torsion part of the Dade\ngroup.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Nov 2011 09:39:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-11-16"}
